Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
delete_feedthru_buffer(25.10)                    delete_feedthru_buffer(25.10)

Name
       delete_feedthru_buffer  -  Removes  the feedthrough buffer specified in
       the -bufInst option

Syntax
        delete_feedthru_buffer

       [-help]

       [-dontDelDanglingPort]

       [-non_preferred_keep_nets <netNamePattern>]

       [-preferred_keep_nets <netNamePattern>]

       {{-bufInst <bufInstName>} | {-instPrefix instPrefixName}

       Removes the feedthrough buffer specified in  the  -bufInst  option.  It
       also  removes  all  possible  dangling hterms/hnets that are associated
       with the buffer removed. The  delete_feedthru_buffer  command  supports
       multiple-instantiated buffer cells.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes the type and default
              information for each delete_feedthru_buffer parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man delete_feedthru_buffer

       -bufInst bufInstName
              Specifies the name of the feedthrough buffer to be removed.

       -dontDelDanglingPort
              Is used if you do not want to remove the dangling ports  created
              by this command.

       -instPrefix instPrefixName
              Specifies the prefix name for the feedthrough buffer. It removes
              all  buffer  instances  that  were  created  by  the  insertPtn-
              Feedthrough command if  insertPtnFeedthrough also used this  op-
              tion  to specify the exactly same instPrefixName. Therefore, you
              need to specify exactly the same instance  name  prefix  in  the
              -instPrefix option of both the commands.

              Note:  The  -instPrefix specified here must be unique to all in-
              stance names in the current design.

       -non_preferred_keep_nets <netNamePattern>
              Specifies the non-preferred keep  net  name  pattern.  The  nets
              whose  names  match the pattern will not be used by buffer dele-
              tion.

       -preferred_keep_nets <netNamePattern>
              Specifies the preferred keep net name pattern.  The  nets  whose
              names match the pattern will be used by buffer deletion.

Example
       The  following  command deletes feedthrough buffer i1/i2/FE_FEED_BUF_1,
       and also keeps the dangling ports:

       delete_feedthru_buffer -bufInst  i1/i2/FE_FEED_BUF_1  -dontDelDangling-
       Port

